data.content:
## Migration Analysis

Your code matches the **Timeout enforcement** pattern. It uses three APIs removed in .NET 6+:

| Removed API | Issue in .NET 8 |
|---|---|
| `Thread.Abort()` | Throws `PlatformNotSupportedException` |
| `ThreadAbortException` | Never thrown — dead catch block |
| `Thread.ResetAbort()` | Throws `PlatformNotSupportedException` |

## Migrated Code (.NET 8)

The replacement uses `CancellationTokenSource.CancelAfter` with `Task.Run`:

```csharp
public class TimedExecutor
{
    public T ExecuteWithTimeout<T>(Func<T> work, TimeSpan timeout)
    {
        using var cts = new CancellationTokenSource(timeout);

        try
        {
            var task = Task.Run(work, cts.Token);
            task.Wait(cts.Token);
            return task.Result;
        }
        catch (OperationCanceledException) when (cts.IsCancellationRequested)
        {
            throw new TimeoutException($"Operation exceeded {timeout.TotalSeconds}s timeout");
        }
        catch (AggregateException ex) when (ex.InnerExceptions.Count == 1)
        {
            throw new AggregateException(ex.InnerException!);
        }
    }

    // Preferred: async overload for new callers
    public async Task<T> ExecuteWithTimeoutAsync<T>(
        Func<CancellationToken, Task<T>> work, TimeSpan timeout)
    {
        using var cts = new CancellationTokenSource(timeout);

        try
        {
            return await work(cts.Token);
        }
        catch (OperationCanceledException) when (cts.IsCancellationRequested)
        {
            throw new TimeoutException($"Operation exceeded {timeout.TotalSeconds}s timeout");
        }
    }
}
```

## Key Pitfalls

| Pitfall | What to do |
|---|---|
| **Cancellation is cooperative, not instant** | Unlike `Thread.Abort`, cancelling the token does NOT forcibly stop `work`. If `work` is a long CPU-bound loop, it must check `token.ThrowIfCancellationRequested()` at regular intervals or it will run to completion. |
| **Blocking I/O won't interrupt** | `Thread.Sleep`, `socket.Receive`, etc. ignore the token. Pass the token to async I/O overloads or use `token.WaitHandle.WaitOne(ms)` instead of `Thread.Sleep`. |
| **Forgetting to dispose `CancellationTokenSource`** | It's `IDisposable` — leaking it causes timer leaks. Always `using`. |
| **Swallowing `OperationCanceledException`** | Only catch it at the top-level orchestration point (as shown). Let it propagate through intermediate layers. |

## If `work` Cannot Be Modified

If the delegate is opaque code you don't control (can't add token checks), **no in-process mechanism in .NET 8 can forcibly stop it**. The only option is to run it in a **separate process** and call `Process.Kill()` on timeout:

```csharp
// Last resort for uncooperative code
var process = Process.Start("WorkerApp.exe", args);
if (!process.WaitForExit(timeout))
{
    process.Kill(entireProcessTree: true);
    throw new TimeoutException("...");
}
```

The sync `ExecuteWithTimeout<T>(Func<T>, TimeSpan)` overload preserves your existing call sites. Migrate callers to the async overload when possible — it flows cancellation properly through the entire call chain.
